{"ts": "2026-06-12T00:22:02.000Z", "event": "planner", "msg": "L3 task decomposition", "agent": "planner-l3", "tokens_in": 801, "tokens_out": 2174, "elapsed_ms": 42669, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Level 3 Planner. Decompose the user task into subtasks for dynamic agent creation.\n\nOutput JSON:\n{{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {{\"task_id\": \"short-name\", \"description\": \"What this worker must produce — ALWAYS include the user's exact request at the top\"}}\n  ]\n}}\n\n## Critical Rules\n- Each subtask description MUST begin with \"USER REQUEST: <exact user task text>\" — this prevents worker hallucination\n- Each subtask must be focused, self-contained, with explicit output file names\n- Never create duplicate task_ids — each worker name must be unique\n- For simple tasks, 3-4 subtasks; for complex tasks, 4-6\n- Always include a \"tester\" as the FINAL subtask — running test_report.json validation\n- Specify exact file names each worker must produce (e.g. \"Write to styles.css\", \"Write to app.js\")\n- Workers receive NO prior context beyond their subtask description — be thorough in the description\n- Output ONLY the JSON object — no markdown fences, no extra text\n\n## Specialty\nfrontend\n\n## User Request\nBuild an accessible landing page for a non-profit environmental organization called \"GreenFuture\". Deliver as index.html, styles.css, app.js, and a11y_report.md.\n\nThe page must be fully conformant with WCAG 2.1 Level AA. Specific requirements:\n- All images have descriptive alt text (not empty, not \"image\")\n- All form inputs have associated <label> with for attribute\n- Heading hierarchy is sequential: h1 → h2 → h3 (never skip levels)\n- All text has minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background\n- A \"Skip to main content\" link is the first focusable element\n- All interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls) are keyboard-accessible\n- Use semantic HTML5: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\n- ARIA labels where semantic elements are insufficient\n\nDeliver a11y_report.md listing every accessibility rule applied and how it was implemented.\n\nFor frontend tasks, you MUST follow these constraints:\n- Always include a final \"integration\" subtask that merges all content/fragments into index.html\n- Always include a \"tester\" subtask as the VERY LAST subtask\n- Good decomposition: [content, html_structure, styling, interactivity, integration, tester]\n- Bad decomposition: [hero_builder, features_builder, cta_builder] — these create standalone pages\n- Each subtask description MUST include the user's verbatim request text at the top\n- Section subtasks produce content fragments into shared files, NOT standalone HTML files\n- The pipeline produces ONE web page: index.html + styles.css + app.js\n\n## CSS-HTML Coordination\n- The HTML worker MUST add semantic CSS classes to every major section (class=\"hero\", class=\"features\", class=\"cta\", class=\"footer\" etc.)\n- The styling worker's subtask MUST say: \"read_file('index.html') FIRST. Write CSS selectors matching the EXACT classes/IDs/elements found in index.html. Do NOT invent new class names.\"\n- The integration subtask MUST include: \"1) read index.html to see classes used, 2) read content.txt for real text, 3) read styles.css to see which classes need to exist, 4) write_file('index.html') with content injected AND missing CSS classes added, 5) read_file('index.html') to verify.\"\n\n## Token Efficiency\n- Each worker≈100K token budget limit for the entire pipeline, plan your decomposition and worker complexity accordingly\n- Avoid micro-workers that do trivial tasks — combine related work into fewer, more substantial workers\n- The CSS/styling worker should NOT call validate_css more than 3 times total", "meta": {}}
{"ts": "2026-06-12T00:22:37.000Z", "event": "agent_creator", "msg": "Agent Creator L3 — generating workers", "agent": "agent-creator-l3", "tokens_in": 3208, "tokens_out": 3114, "elapsed_ms": 34639, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Advanced Agent Creator (Level 3 — Fully Autonomous). Your role: create worker agents from scratch with custom system instructions, tools, and dynamic code tools.\n\n## Available Tools\nThe tool menu for this specialty:\n[\"read_file\", \"write_file\", \"list_files\", \"run_command\", \"render_html_screenshot\", \"render_html_file_screenshot\", \"validate_html\", \"validate_css\", \"read_image\", \"generate_image\"]\n\n## Task Plan\nThe planner has decomposed the task into subtasks:\n{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"content\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build an accessible landing page for a non-profit environmental organization called \\\"GreenFuture\\\". Deliver as index.html, styles.css, app.js, and a11y_report.md.\\n\\nThe page must be fully conformant with WCAG 2.1 Level AA. Specific requirements:\\n- All images have descriptive alt text (not empty, not \\\"image\\\")\\n- All form inputs have associated <label> with for attribute\\n- Heading hierarchy is sequential: h1 \\u2192 h2 \\u2192 h3 (never skip levels)\\n- All text has minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background\\n- A \\\"Skip to main content\\\" link is the first focusable element\\n- All interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls) are keyboard-accessible\\n- Use semantic HTML5: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\\n- ARIA labels where semantic elements are insufficient\\n\\nDeliver a11y_report.md listing every accessibility rule applied and how it was implemented.\\n\\nWrite the full textual content for the landing page including hero section, mission statement, key initiatives, newsletter signup form, and footer. Ensure all content is concise, inspiring, and aligned with an environmental nonprofit. Write to content.txt using semantic section markers: <!-- HERO -->, <!-- MISSION -->, <!-- INITIATIVES -->, <!-- NEWSLETTER -->, <!-- FOOTER -->. Do not include HTML structure or styling.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"html_structure\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build an accessible landing page for a non-profit environmental organization called \\\"GreenFuture\\\". Deliver as index.html, styles.css, app.js, and a11y_report.md.\\n\\nThe page must be fully conformant with WCAG 2.1 Level AA. Specific requirements:\\n- All images have descriptive alt text (not empty, not \\\"image\\\")\\n- All form inputs have associated <label> with for attribute\\n- Heading hierarchy is sequential: h1 \\u2192 h2 \\u2192 h3 (never skip levels)\\n- All text has minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background\\n- A \\\"Skip to main content\\\" link is the first focusable element\\n- All interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls) are keyboard-accessible\\n- Use semantic HTML5: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\\n- ARIA labels where semantic elements are insufficient\\n\\nDeliver a11y_report.md listing every accessibility rule applied and how it was implemented.\\n\\nCreate a valid HTML5 document structure in index.html. Begin with <!DOCTYPE html>, include <html lang=\\\"en\\\">, <head> with meta tags (charset, viewport, description), and <title>GreenFuture \\u2013 Protecting Our Planet</title>. Implement: \\n- First focusable element is a 'Skip to main content' link\\n- Use semantic elements: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\\n- Add placeholder <img> tags with descriptive alt attributes (e.g., alt=\\\"Volunteers planting trees in urban area\\\")\\n- Include a newsletter signup form with <label for=\\\"email\\\"> and <input id=\\\"email\\\">\\n- Assign semantic CSS classes: class=\\\"hero\\\", class=\\\"mission\\\", class=\\\"initiatives\\\", class=\\\"cta\\\", class=\\\"footer\\\"\\n- Do NOT include inline styles or scripts\\nWrite to index.html\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"styling\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build an accessible landing page for a non-profit environmental organization called \\\"GreenFuture\\\". Deliver as index.html, styles.css, app.js, and a11y_report.md.\\n\\nThe page must be fully conformant with WCAG 2.1 Level AA. Specific requirements:\\n- All images have descriptive alt text (not empty, not \\\"image\\\")\\n- All form inputs have associated <label> with for attribute\\n- Heading hierarchy is sequential: h1 \\u2192 h2 \\u2192 h3 (never skip levels)\\n- All text has minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background\\n- A \\\"Skip to main content\\\" link is the first focusable element\\n- All interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls) are keyboard-accessible\\n- Use semantic HTML5: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\\n- ARIA labels where semantic elements are insufficient\\n\\nDeliver a11y_report.md listing every accessibility rule applied and how it was implemented.\\n\\nread_file('index.html') FIRST. Write CSS selectors matching the EXACT classes/IDs/elements found in index.html. Do NOT invent new class names. Write to styles.css with responsive, accessible styling:\\n- Ensure all text-background combinations meet minimum 4.5:1 contrast ratio (use verified color pairs)\\n- Visually hide the 'Skip to main content' link off-screen until focused\\n- Style interactive elements (buttons, links, inputs) to show clear focus states\\n- Use relative units (em, rem) for scalable typography\\n- Ensure layout is responsive on mobile and desktop\\n- Do NOT use color alone to convey information\\nValidate CSS with validate_css(styles.css) up to 3 times only. Write final output to styles.css\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"interactivity\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build an accessible landing page for a non-profit environmental organization called \\\"GreenFuture\\\". Deliver as index.html, styles.css, app.js, and a11y_report.md.\\n\\nThe page must be fully conformant with WCAG 2.1 Level AA. Specific requirements:\\n- All images have descriptive alt text (not empty, not \\\"image\\\")\\n- All form inputs have associated <label> with for attribute\\n- Heading hierarchy is sequential: h1 \\u2192 h2 \\u2192 h3 (never skip levels)\\n- All text has minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background\\n- A \\\"Skip to main content\\\" link is the first focusable element\\n- All interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls) are keyboard-accessible\\n- Use semantic HTML5: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\\n- ARIA labels where semantic elements are insufficient\\n\\nDeliver a11y_report.md listing every accessibility rule applied and how it was implemented.\\n\\nImplement JavaScript interactivity in app.js:\\n- Smooth scrolling behavior for 'Skip to main content' link\\n- Form validation for newsletter signup (check for valid email format)\\n- Display success message on valid submission (prevent default form submission)\\n- Ensure all interactions are keyboard-triggerable and do not trap focus\\n- Use ARIA live regions if dynamic content updates occur\\nWrite to app.js\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"integration\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build an accessible landing page for a non-profit environmental organization called \\\"GreenFuture\\\". Deliver as index.html, styles.css, app.js, and a11y_report.md.\\n\\nThe page must be fully conformant with WCAG 2.1 Level AA. Specific requirements:\\n- All images have descriptive alt text (not empty, not \\\"image\\\")\\n- All form inputs have associated <label> with for attribute\\n- Heading hierarchy is sequential: h1 \\u2192 h2 \\u2192 h3 (never skip levels)\\n- All text has minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background\\n- A \\\"Skip to main content\\\" link is the first focusable element\\n- All interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls) are keyboard-accessible\\n- Use semantic HTML5: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\\n- ARIA labels where semantic elements are insufficient\\n\\nDeliver a11y_report.md listing every accessibility rule applied and how it was implemented.\\n\\n1) read index.html to see classes used, 2) read content.txt for real text, 3) read styles.css to see which classes need to exist, 4) write_file('index.html') with content injected AND missing CSS classes added, 5) read_file('index.html') to verify. Inject content from content.txt into corresponding sections of index.html (e.g., <!-- HERO --> replaced with actual hero content). Ensure all semantic classes are present. Confirm <script src=\\\"app.js\\\"> and <link rel=\\\"stylesheet\\\" href=\\\"styles.css\\\"> are in <head> or before </body>. Final output must be a single, valid, accessible index.html.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"tester\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build an accessible landing page for a non-profit environmental organization called \\\"GreenFuture\\\". Deliver as index.html, styles.css, app.js, and a11y_report.md.\\n\\nThe page must be fully conformant with WCAG 2.1 Level AA. Specific requirements:\\n- All images have descriptive alt text (not empty, not \\\"image\\\")\\n- All form inputs have associated <label> with for attribute\\n- Heading hierarchy is sequential: h1 \\u2192 h2 \\u2192 h3 (never skip levels)\\n- All text has minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background\\n- A \\\"Skip to main content\\\" link is the first focusable element\\n- All interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls) are keyboard-accessible\\n- Use semantic HTML5: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <footer>\\n- ARIA labels where semantic elements are insufficient\\n\\nDeliver a11y_report.md listing every accessibility rule applied and how it was implemented.\\n\\nRun accessibility audit using axe_core on index.html. Generate test_report.json with results. Validate that all WCAG 2.1 Level AA criteria are passed. If failures exist, document them and trigger a rework cycle. If all pass, write a11y_report.md listing each rule applied and how it was implemented (e.g., 'Skip to main content': implemented as first link in <header> with off-screen visibility until focused). Final deliverables: index.html, styles.css, app.js, a11y_report.md, test_report.json.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\n## Specialty-Specific Architecture Constraints\nFor FRONTEND specialty:\n- One worker MUST produce index.html as the canonical entry page\n- All CSS lives in ONE shared styles.css file. All JavaScript in ONE shared app.js file.\n- Workers write SECTIONS INTO these shared files — they do NOT create standalone HTML pages.\n- If you create section-specific workers (hero, features, cta),\n  the pipeline MUST end with an integrator that merges all sections\n  into a single index.html with linked styles.css and app.js.\n- Never design a pipeline where each worker produces its own standalone HTML page.\n- The user expects ONE complete web page, not a collection of separate HTML files.\n\n## HTML-CSS Coordination (CRITICAL — prevents broken pages)\nEvery CSS worker system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'iCRITICAL: read_file(\"index.html\") FIRST before writing any CSS. Your selectors MUST match actual elements/classes/IDs in the HTML.'\n- 'Use the SAME class naming convention as the HTML. If HTML uses class=\"hero\", write .hero {{}}. Never invent new class names.'\nEvery HTML worker system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'Add semantic CSS classes to ALL major sections: class=\"header\", class=\"hero\", class=\"features\", class=\"cta\", class=\"footer\" etc.'\n- 'Use class selectors (not just bare element tags) so the CSS worker can target them reliably.'\nEvery integrator system_prompt MUST include:\n- '1. read_file(\"index.html\") to see current HTML structure and classes'\n- '2. Inject real content from content.txt INTO the existing HTML — do NOT rewrite the HTML from scratch'\n- '3. Add any missing CSS classes to elements that the stylesheet targets'\n- '4. write_file(\"index.html\", ...) to save — NEVER skip this step'\n- '5. read_file(\"index.html\") to verify the merge succeeded'\n\n## Conversation History & Memory Protocol (MUST include in every worker prompt)\nEvery worker's system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'Your conversation history is LIMITED. The LLM only sees the last 3 tool-call turns.'\n- 'Use WORKSPACE FILES as your persistent memory — always read_file() at start of iteration.'\n- 'Do NOT re-read unchanged files — use list_files to verify existence instead.'\n- 'Tool results from read_file are truncated to 3000 chars and cached.'\n- 'After completing, write exactly ONE final output file and STOP. Do not iterate needlessly.'\n\n\n## Your Job\nFor EACH subtask in the plan:\n1. WRITE a custom system_prompt from scratch — give the worker clear role, boundaries, and workflow\n2. SELECT tools from the available tool menu that the worker needs\n3. If available tools are insufficient, CREATE dynamic_tools as Python code strings\n4. Optionally create inline_skills as text fragments (not loaded from files)\n\n## Dynamic Tools (Python code strings)\nDynamic tools are Python functions the worker can call. Write them as complete, executable code strings.\nExample:\n  \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \"fetch_api\", \"code\": \"import httpx\\nasync def fetch_api(url):\\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as c:\\n        return (await c.get(url)).text\", \"description\": \"Fetch data from an API\"}]\n\n## Rules\n- Output ONLY valid JSON — no markdown fences, no extra text\n- worker_name: give each worker a unique short name (e.g. \"scraper\", \"analyzer\", \"validator\")\n- system_prompt: must be detailed — role, boundaries, tools to use, workflow, output format\n- tool_names: only from the available tool menu\n- dynamic_tools: list of {name, code, description} — only create if needed\n- inline_skills: list of prompt fragments for worker knowledge\n\n## Output Format\n{\n  \"workers\": [\n    {\n      \"worker_name\": \"unique_name\",\n      \"system_prompt\": \"Full custom system instructions\",\n      \"tool_names\": [\"tool1\", \"tool2\"],\n      \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \".\", \"code\": \".\", \"description\": \".\"}],\n      \"inline_skills\": [\"Skill fragment text...\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "meta": {}}
